title: Manfrotto MKC3-H01 Camera Tripod Attachment Plate
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The Manfrotto MKC3-H01 camera tripod uses a non-standard attachment plate to mate the camera with the stand. Rather than replace an otherwise fantastic camera tripod, or pay the $25 for a replacement plate, this piece was designed.

This is the attachment plate only. The wingnut, washer collar, alignment pin and spring were taken from a cheap, more standard attachment plate. You can add a few layers of duct tape (or cork tape), trimmed to size on the top of the plate, where the camera mates to the plate for more friction. If your camera has an alignment hole, the pin will hold it in place and the tape is not necessary.

It works great, and saves quite a bit of money over purchasing a replacement. I have printed two and use them both regularly.

I know this may not be a piece that most people will need or use, but just in case I thought I'd upload it.

title: VLight - minimalistic light solution for VORON

description.text:
Since I moved my printer to the appliances room I started to use a webcam to monitor whether the printer is working correctly or not. Apparently my webcam has a crappy low light capabilities and therefore I needed some kind of additional light source to get things to look half decent. I thought that it would be kind of good idea to add a separate controllable light to the printer instead of keeping the room lights on all the time. So here is the result.

Included the Solidworks files as well for easy remixing. :D

E: Solidworks file is for SW17 and up.
E1: Added 365 mm for 12" Vorons and 280 mm version if you want to use the volcom8190 idler assembly with regular Voron.

Printer:

Voron 1.5

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

0,2 mm

Infill:

20-30%

Notes:

Easy print, does not need any special instructions.

Things you need
  • LED strip (https://goo.gl/QAQVkX)
  • 4x DIN 912 M5 8 mm bolts
  • 4x Tnuts
  • Enough wire to reach you electronics
  • Some crimps (optional)
  • Better adhesive tape (the one that comes with LED-s is kind of shit)

Print out both pieces (easiest puzzle ever!). After that you can cut the LED strip to the length and pull the wire through the little slot on the part. Both pieces have slots so there's a option which side to use.

When preparing the wire ends for the soldering leave the positive wire a bit longer than a negative. This makes soldering and further wiring a bit easier since you don't have to mess with redundant wire. Remove half of the adhesive and clue LED strip to the place. Combine both pieces and mount them to the frame. Fold the wire to the extrusion like this. It should look like this from the top.

Duet Wifi

I run a single extruder setup so I had second extruder contacts vacant.

Add M307 H2 A-1 C-1 D-1 to the config.g. This code disables the second heater and allows to use it for other purposes.
For switching lights make a macro which consist of following code: M42 P2 Sxxx where xxx is the value from 0 to 255. (0 is off and 255 is maximum brightness). I added the same gcode to the starting and ending script of my printer so the lights will turn automatically on when printer starts working and off when printer is idle.

RAMPS etc.

Just search from youtube: How to add software-controlled LEDs to your 3D printer!
(can't add a direct link because thingiverse automatically embedded it to my gallery which is not what i wanted to do).

To quickly tally trees in a repeatable way that provides useful information about the volume of wood and diversity of tree species many foresters will complete a variable distance plot. The tool required is often either a wedge prism or an angle gauge. The wedge prisms can cost $40-80 dollars and is fairly difficult to make. An angle gauge is much easier to make, is a lot cheaper (pennies), and will provide comparable results. How to use an angle gauge is explained well enough on Wikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle_gauge This tool only takes minutes to print so producing a class set should be relatively quick and easy. I have compared the results from this angle gauge to a wedge prism and had essentially identical results.

description.text:
This is bookmark that I modelled after the game Tens! (https://tensga.me) that we created at Kwalee.

After I printed a few harry potter bookmarks and distributed them around the office I noticed that a lot of people where using them, so I decided to model a bookmark after our game, the dice theme looked nice and I had the right colour filament (bought to make prints for my nieces).

I'm releasing the STL and the Source file in openscad.

Using the openscad file you can change one variable to get any dice number from 1 to 6 or you can remove the dice altogether and add your own bookmark head.

Printed mine multi-colour using the prusa's color print (changes filament after a certain layer height). the base part is 0.4mm so printing with 0.2mm layers the color print change layer should be set to 0.6mm (this always gets me).
The dice head is 1mm thick so the whole thing is only 5 layers tall using 0.2mm.

Filling up my Prusa Mk2s I can print 21 at the time in 1hr44ms (with the colour change).

Enjoy!

description.text:
Glueless wheels for 1/10 RC cars. I may add more sizes later on if I have some tires to test with. They have 12mm hex.

I haven't tried the 2WD front wheels yet.

Paypal donations are welcome if you want me to continue posting my designs..

Back in the 80's many competition cars had three piece wheels and tires and didn't always require glue. I think that was a good thing because you can change tires or wheels as often as you like.

The wheels have the same offset as competition wheels by Schumacher and conform to the regulations in width and diameter. The center ring is larger than the allowed 60 mm diameter, but I don't kow if that matters to the rule makers. It's hidden in the tire. The rear wheel is for both 4WD and 2WD rear wheel use. The front wheel is mainly for 4WD, but fit 2WD cars with 12mm hex as well.

The wheels I printed spin perfectly true, unlike many one piece wheels out there. It's also possible to reassemble it if a tire is installed wonky, whereas glued tires are less forgiving.

There are two ring sizes. Some tires need the loose ring and some the tight ring. I installed Schumacher 2.2" tires with the loose ring. I installed cheap chinese tires with the tight ring. The ring can also be resized in your slizer if you need further adjustment, like if a tire can't be assembled in the wheel. The tire will look strained with just the ring in place, but it will need to be tight to stay in place once assembled. It can be a little difficult getting the rings into some tires, like the Schumachers which are tight tires.

Punch a hole in the tire carcass if you want it to breathe.

The wheels require the following screws:
-4x M2x6 for each front wheel
-4X M2x12 for each rear wheel

Notes:

PLA. 100% infill and two perimeters is good.

The outside cap for the front wheels should be printed at very fine height resolution for best looks. I used 0.06 mm layer height on them.

description.text:
Hi, there

Since my printer got a nice and huge housing, I needed a filament guide.
The search on Thingiverse gave a thousands of versions, but all of them
were for a specific printer, a specific case or just over engineered.

So I use my recently growing FreeCAD skills and build my own simple
design.

I added three different versions. One without a cut and two with a cut
for on the fly swapping the filament. The cut is diagonal to avoid
loosing the filament. I added two directions of the cut for optimal
guidance.

All versions are suited to guide 1.75 mm and 3 mm
filament.

However the cut version probably needs a little force to get filament
bigger than 1.75 mm though the side gap. If you need a bigger slot
just adapt the sketch using FreeCAD.

Both FreeCAD files are included, so you can modify the design if needed.

Happy Printing.

Complete redesign of our universal Wade with some Improvements.
Should fit all Printer with 50mm Mounting holes ( V9 Hotend only testet on uniX-Carriage and Orca)
Thanks to Daniel for ideas and testing :)
  • Stepper moved to bottom
  • Idler now has a Tubeholder
  • filament Inlet closer to the bolt
  • Optimized to work with uniX-Carriage http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:25420
    • additional Features
  • 1,75mm and 3mm Filament Support
  • compatible with J-Head/Groovemount/Reprapfab/Geeksbase/Mendelparts V9/10 and probably alot of other Hotends
    • Feature Removed:
  • Lots of mounting holes - back to only 50mm default mounting holes
    • I made a Prusa uniX-Carriage for test purpose http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:25600 Update 01.09.2012:
  • Minor Fixes and print optimization (v 1.1)
  • Fanholder for direct mount on Extruder
  • new V9 Inset, mount like shown on the picture, no Metal plate needed anymore !!!

Shoppinglist Main parts: 1x M8x50/60mm hobbed bolt
5x M8 washer
2x M8 Nut
1x 8x20mm bolt (or a cutoff of a M8 bolt) for the Idler
2x M4x60mm screw
2x M4 washer
2x M4 Nut
2x spring for Wade (~ 5mm diameter and 10mm lenth, depending on its strengh)
3x 608 bearing
3x M3x30 screw (one for the idler two for the inset)
3x M3 washer
4x M3 nut
1x M3 worm screw (?)
4x M3x10mm Screw (for Stepper mounting)
2x M4 Nylock nut`s for mounting the wade
2x M4 Screw , lenght depending on the Carriage you are using. Additional parts for Mendel-Parts V9 / V10:
1x 28x32x2mm thick metal plate, cut and drilled to fit into the printed "carrierplate" and then drill the holes
1x M6 brassnut
2x M4 Nylock nut
2x M4x15 screw For 1,75mm filament printing you need a brasstube with d=2,4mm / D=3mm Print all Extruder parts and the Inset of your Hotend. there are two version of the insets, one with 16,7mm for well tuned printer, and one with 16,4mm for not so well tuned printer ;) *I Uploaded pictures to show how it is assembled (would take me too long to write all down, sorry guy`s)
  • the metal plate is only required for V9/V10 hotend, but give also stability with other hotends.
    • *For Reprapfab/Geeksbase Hotend you need to rasp the screws square and press them (from left to right) tight to the hotend when mounting.
    the important corner is on the upside of the hotend (Pictures show only the lower side !)

  • For Mendel-Parts Hotend on the original plate you have just to print the inset.
    First mount the Hotend on the carriage (use a additional screw beneath the plate) and then put on the Extruder.

  • For mounting the Extruder to the stock Orca V40/42 metal plate you need to drill one additional hole ( www.thingiverse.com/image:136320 ) and change the Screws on the back to countersunk screws.
    • * For Mendel-Parts Hotend on uniX-Carriage you have to make a small iron(or steel) plate (28x34x2mm).
    -Print the "carriertemplate.stl" and put the plate into it to mark where the holes should be drilled at.
    Make the middle hole about 7mm and the outer 4,5mm.

  • Iron Plate is not needed anymore, just print the new short V9 inset (maybe a second time for filling the hole on the upper side) and screw it tight between two nut`s (like shown on the picture)
    ensure that the indentation of the inset stands in the right direction

  • If you want to use 1,75mm filament you need a brasstube with inner diameter 2,4mm and outer 3mm ( http://www.conrad.de/ce/de/product/222337/ )
  • First put the Extruder with the hotend all together then measure how deep the filament hole from the middle of the bolt to the hotend is and cut it a little bit shorter.
    Now rasp the upper end sharp as shown on the picture.
    IMPORTANT smooth the edge of the Upperside or the filament will cut into the insert !
    • additinal pictures can be found here: http://imageshack.us/g/6/unixwade15.jpg/
